    33‚Üí/// A value in a key-value.
    34‚Üí///
    35‚Üí/// Values are an anonymous bag containing some structured datum.
    36‚Üí///
    37‚Üí/// # Capturing values
    38‚Üí///
    39‚Üí/// There are a few ways to capture a value:
    40‚Üí///
    41‚Üí/// - Using the `Value::from_*` methods.
    42‚Üí/// - Using the `ToValue` trait.
    43‚Üí/// - Using the standard `From` trait.
    44‚Üí///
    45‚Üí/// ## Using the `Value::from_*` methods
    46‚Üí///
    47‚Üí/// `Value` offers a few constructor methods that capture values of different kinds.
    48‚Üí///
    49‚Üí/// ```
    50‚Üí/// use log::kv::Value;
    51‚Üí///
    52‚Üí/// let value = Value::from_debug(&42i32);
    53‚Üí///
    54‚Üí/// assert_eq!(None, value.to_i64());
    55‚Üí/// ```
    56‚Üí///
    57‚Üí/// ## Using the `ToValue` trait
    58‚Üí///
    59‚Üí/// The `ToValue` trait can be used to capture values generically.
    60‚Üí/// It's the bound used by `Source`.
    61‚Üí///
    62‚Üí/// ```
    63‚Üí/// # use log::kv::ToValue;
    64‚Üí/// let value = 42i32.to_value();
    65‚Üí///
    66‚Üí/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    67‚Üí/// ```
    68‚Üí///
    69‚Üí/// ## Using the standard `From` trait
    70‚Üí///
    71‚Üí/// Standard types that implement `ToValue` also implement `From`.
    72‚Üí///
    73‚Üí/// ```
    74‚Üí/// use log::kv::Value;
    75‚Üí///
    76‚Üí/// let value = Value::from(42i32);
    77‚Üí///
    78‚Üí/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    79‚Üí/// ```
    80‚Üí///
    81‚Üí/// # Data model
    82‚Üí///
    83‚Üí/// Values can hold one of a number of types:
    84‚Üí///
    85‚Üí/// - **Null:** The absence of any other meaningful value. Note that
    86‚Üí///   `Some(Value::null())` is not the same as `None`. The former is
    87‚Üí///   `null` while the latter is `undefined`. This is important to be
    88‚Üí///   able to tell the difference between a key-value that was logged,
    89‚Üí///   but its value was empty (`Some(Value::null())`) and a key-value
    90‚Üí///   that was never logged at all (`None`).
    91‚Üí/// - **Strings:** `str`, `char`.
    92‚Üí/// - **Booleans:** `bool`.
    93‚Üí/// - **Integers:** `u8`-`u128`, `i8`-`i128`, `NonZero*`.
    94‚Üí/// - **Floating point numbers:** `f32`-`f64`.
    95‚Üí/// - **Errors:** `dyn (Error + 'static)`.
    96‚Üí/// - **`serde`:** Any type in `serde`'s data model.
    97‚Üí/// - **`sval`:** Any type in `sval`'s data model.
    98‚Üí///
    99‚Üí/// # Serialization
   100‚Üí///
   101‚Üí/// Values provide a number of ways to be serialized.
   102‚Üí///
   103‚Üí/// For basic types the [`Value::visit`] method can be used to extract the
   104‚Üí/// underlying typed value. However, this is limited in the amount of types
   105‚Üí/// supported (see the [`VisitValue`] trait methods).
   106‚Üí///
   107‚Üí/// For more complex types one of the following traits can be used:
   108‚Üí///  * `sval::Value`, requires the `kv_sval` feature.
   109‚Üí///  * `serde::Serialize`, requires the `kv_serde` feature.
   110‚Üí///
   111‚Üí/// You don't need a visitor to serialize values through `serde` or `sval`.
   112‚Üí///
   113‚Üí/// A value can always be serialized using any supported framework, regardless
   114‚Üí/// of how it was captured. If, for example, a value was captured using its
   115‚Üí/// `Display` implementation, it will serialize through `serde` as a string. If it was
   116‚Üí/// captured as a struct using `serde`, it will also serialize as a struct
   117‚Üí/// through `sval`, or can be formatted using a `Debug`-compatible representation.
   118‚Üí#[derive(Clone)]
   119‚Üípub struct Value<'v> {
   123‚Üíimpl<'v> Value<'v> {
   124‚Üí    /// Get a value from a type implementing `ToValue`.
